        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(mentions): support single-char CJK names in mention pattern matching",
        "body": "fix(mentions): support single-char CJK names in mention pattern matching\n\n## Summary\n**Problem:** The `\\b` word boundary assertion in JavaScript regex does not recognise CJK characters as word characters. When an agent identity name is a single CJK character (e.g. \"包\"), the derived mention pattern `\\b@?包\\b` fails to match `@包` in group chat messages. This affected DingTalk/钉钉 and other Chinese group chat channels.\n\n**Fix:** Added a `wrapWithBoundaries` helper in `deriveMentionPatterns` that detects CJK characters in the pattern and replaces `\\b` with explicit Unicode-aware lookaround assertions. ASCII-only patterns continue to use `\\b` unchanged.\n\n**Out of scope:** No changes to extension-specific mention parsers. Only the core shared `deriveMentionPatterns` function is affected.\n\n## Linked context\nCloses #87303\n\n## Real behavior proof\n\n- Behavior or issue addressed: Single-char CJK mention names (e.g. @包) were not detected as mentions in group chat messages because `\\b` does not work with CJK characters in JavaScript regex\n- Real environment tested: Windows 10, Node.js v22.11.0, OpenClaw latest main (commit 70a989a, 2026-06-03)\n- Exact steps or command run after this patch: Ran OpenClaw's actual `buildMentionRegexes` helper via `node --import tsx proof-87303.mjs` with a real `agents.list` config containing a CJK identity name\n- Evidence after fix: Terminal output from running OpenClaw's production `buildMentionRegexes` and `matchesMentionPatterns` helpers:\n```\n$ node --import tsx proof-87303.mjs\nregex count: 1\npattern: (?:(?<=^)|(?<![w一-鿿㐀-䶿]))@?包(?![w一-鿿㐀-䶿])\n\n--- Single-char CJK mention tests ---\n@包 你好 => true\n包 你好 => true\n面包好吃 => false\n\n--- Two-char CJK mention tests ---\n@苏苏 你好 => true\n紫苏苏叶 => false\n```\n- Observed result after fix: `buildMentionRegexes` with `agents.list: [{ id: \"cjk-agent\", identity: { name: \"包\" } }]` produces a regex that correctly matches `@包` in Chinese text and correctly rejects `面包好吃` (no false positive inside longer CJK word). Two-char CJK names (`苏苏`) also work correctly.\n- What was not tested: Live DingTalk group chat end-to-end test (requires DingTalk bot credentials)\n\n## Tests and validation\n- `src/auto-reply/reply/mentions.test.ts`: New `describe(\"CJK single-char mention matching (regression #87303)\")` — 5 tests using `agents.list` config shape with concrete agent id\n- No CHANGELOG.md edits\n\n## Risk checklist\n- userVisible: No\n- configEnvMigration: No\n- securityAuthNetwork: No\n- Mitigation: ASCII-only patterns unchanged; CJK path uses standard lookaround assertions\n\n## Current review state\n- Addressed ClawSweeper P1: Fixed tests to use `agents.list` with concrete agent id\n- Addressed ClawSweeper P1: Added real after-fix proof running OpenClaw's `buildMentionRegexes` helper\n- [x] AI-assisted (built with Claude Code)\n",
        "branch": "fix/87303-cjk-single-char-mention",
